<div id="comment_status_64625025" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64625025" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64625025" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64625025" name="comment_link_64625025" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23387245&amp;cid=64625025" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64625025)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64625025" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64625025); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~AmiMoJo">AmiMoJo</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~AmiMoJo">( 196126 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64625025"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64625025"><p>Generally speaking EV batteries are arranged as modules, with each module containing a number of cells. Mostly it is not possible to replace individual cells, only modules. Depending on the design, the modules can be quite reasonably priced.</p><p>I'm sure you could replace cells with some hacking, but manufacturers don't support that, it's only at the module level. Then you have the rest of the battery, the case, internal electronics, thermal management system. Often the case is a large cast block.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64625025">

</div>
</div>

